Anonymous Thu 17 Sep 2020 13:26:49 No.32841745 Report
Quoted By: >>32841876 >>32842009
>>32841401
>>32841430
In my case, spending a year flopping around with "le tried and true methods," spending bigbux on books (which I still own), and keeping a dream journal. Meditation, medi-napping (slipping into REM while conscious through breathing techniques). Then I did it my own way: learn to calmly recognize the signatures you commonly observe in your dreams that TELL you you're dreaming (mine's clocks and broken mirrors). Write down what you see in your dreams immediately (heck, TEXT it to yourself if you live off your phone like me); read your entries and think about it, especially during mundane tasks. Eventually, you'll begin to associate that tactile sense (muscles in motion) with awareness, you'll recognize signatures, and you'll have your lucid "OH!" moments eventually. Don't get too excited, though; you'll start right up in real irl life. I've done this for so long, I "wake up" in my own dreams after start phases and reset. I choose when to rise, unless I feel like I'm going to be late for work, which freaks me the heck out every time. Then I wake up two hours before my alarm, so I just carry on with my morning routine.

I would very much doubt humans and anthros could be sufficiently genetically compatible that they could produce viable offspring. We don't even have any real evidence humans can hybridize with chimps or bonobos, only some scattered unreliable anecdotes and maaaaaybe someone knocking together an embryo in a lab. It's vanishingly unlikely two different species could produce viable offspring.

That being said, it may depend on how anthros came into existence. If they were the result of genetic tampering with humans in the first place, then it's certainly plausible that the outwardly-dramatic differences are trivial under the genetic hood. I mean, to an alien unfamiliar with dogs, I cannot imagine assuming a chihuahua was the same species as a sheepdog. So, if morphology is just a matter of bit-twiddling existing human genes, interbreeding would be no different from, say, a white person and a black person mating.

However, if anthros and humans both naturally evolved, whether from different kinds of less-sentient animals or on different planets, I think hybridizing at all would pretty much require outright magic.

>>32855935
No, I’m fairly certain it should be suppose, else the rest of the paragraph would be past tense. Some sentences can be written in somewhat past tense but be present tense.

Example: “she closed the door” can talk about what just happened, or talk about a past event.
So, “we entered the room and then she closed the door” could be present, and a response could be “I’m not sure what to think about her closing the door” or it could be past tense like “ I’m not sure what I thought about her closing the door”.

Present tense seems to make more contextual sense in the portion I mentioned, because the story seems to be referring to events as they happen, not as they have happened in the past.
Either way works though. English is a dumb language with many intricacies and exceptions that don’t make sense.
I will say that I forgot to mention one other thing. You use commas a lot, even when unnecessary.
Often times you put a comma whenever there would be a pause in a sentence. This is not how commas are supposed to be used.
Example: a sentence like (This isn’t in the story just an example, same as the example earlier) “I went to the bench, then I sat down, after which I stood up” is easily changed to “I went to the bench and sat down. After that I stood up”
The commas not only look messy, they aren’t used very well.
It’s still readable and the writing is great, it’s just that if you submitted this to a proper editor they would have a fucking fit fixing it.

The only reason I don’t point all these errors out is that
1: I am by no means a professional, I’m just some dude with some college experience in writing class. I don’t want to point out a mistake and be wrong.
2: When I am 100% confident a comma is unneeded I still don’t mention it because pointing the mistakes out would make any correction list massive. A single comma isn’t a big enough deal.
